ce:section.ce:para:
As a summary, we have shown that Ag5 nanoclusters are very stable species which can catalyze the complete reduction (as in DPPH

                     ) or oxidation (as in R

                      -polymer degradation-) of radicals producing ONLY non-radical species. Therefore, such nanoclusters represent a new kind of catalysts with unique anti-radical properties, which could be of large importance for industrial or biomedical applications. It would be interesting to see if nanoclusters of other metals (Au, Cu, Pt, etc.) can be even more active than Ag, showing higher selectivity against specific types of radicals. We hope that these results will encourage the development of new methods for the synthesis of monodisperse clusters of other metals.
